pr_review_comment_body:
@gforcada, I've fixed up the USAGE.rst documentation a bit in https://github.com/reinout/z3c.dependencychecker/pull/89/commits/938c4e6f21a380e47c99a6ae3f67a1aeb9d11e54 (I pushed it to your branch).

Does that look OK?

If so: can *you* do the merge + release? Then we know for sure that I set the right permissions on the pypi project :-)

I came up with this, and it works, should protect against a random XML file and bad file extensions:

`def find_file_in_zip(zip, ext):
    for filename in zip.namelist():
        try:
            ET.parse(zip.open(filename)).getroot().tag in ('workbook', 'datasource')
            return filename
        except ET.ParseError:
            # that ain't it
            pass`

Not sure how much better than checking the ext it is though

It is true that this is the same docstring used by `requests` library. But they also provide [intensive documentation](http://docs.python-requests.org/en/master/user/advanced/#proxies) to provide the examples on what "dictionary mapping" actually looks like. Since we don't currently have those documentation effort, I would suggest we at least add one more sentence here. Either explicitly mentions an example:

> Its content will look like `proxies = {
  'http': 'http://10.10.1.10:3128',
  'https': 'http://10.10.1.10:1080',
}`

Or simply add a link to its [official documentation in requests](http://docs.python-requests.org/en/master/user/advanced/#proxies) (since we are exposing this requests behavior anyway).

@althonos This is a notable change. If a required namespace is not present, it raises a `MissingInfoNamespace` which is a subclass of `AttributeError`.

The motivation was the `islink` could have 3 return values; False, True and None. And I really didn't like that.

What do you think?

This does the trick. We either pick:

1. the value at runtime of the search field (altered by user or provided by a `input[value]` attribute;
2. otherwise we pick it up from the query string;
3. otherwise field value has not been setup

@hackaugusto yes, I understood. What I suggested is like:
```
config = {
  'transport': {
    'udpparam1': ...,
    'udpparam2': ...,
    'sharedparam1': ...,
    'matrixparam1': ...
  }
}
```
No udp nor matrix prefixes required, just to exemplify. The idea is that the transport, whichever it be, look for its parameter in the `transport` config. No need to split in separate subkeys/namespaces, each transport will look for the keys it cares, and ignore the others, and it means we only support one transport anyway.

```
return self._tags.get(key, None)
```
